Strong OKR structure (what good looks like)

Instead of just saying “OKRs,” you say:

Objective 1: Build trusted and secure data sharing for customers

Key Results:

% of customers actively managing consent (not just passive opt-in)
Reduction in consent-related support issues
Time taken to revoke or modify permissions
Objective 2: Drive FinTech and aggregator adoption of APIs

Key Results:

Number of active third-party integrations
API call volume / active usage per partner
Time to onboard a new FinTech partner
Objective 3: Ensure platform reliability and compliance

Key Results:

API uptime / latency SLAs
Number of security or compliance incidents (target: near zero)
Audit readiness / successful compliance reviews
Objective 4: Improve developer experience

Key Results:

Developer onboarding time (sandbox → production)
API error rate / integration failure rate
Developer satisfaction score (NPS or feedback loop)
Now here is your upgraded interview answer

You can say:

“I would define success using OKRs across four dimensions. First, customer trust and control—measuring how effectively users understand and manage consent, including revocation behavior and reduction in consent-related friction.

Second, ecosystem adoption—tracking active FinTech integrations, API usage, and time-to-onboard new partners to ensure the platform is actually scaling.

Third, platform reliability and compliance—ensuring strong SLAs around uptime, low incident rates, and audit readiness since this is a regulated data-sharing product.

And finally, developer experience—measuring onboarding time, API error rates, and developer satisfaction to ensure the ecosystem can scale efficiently.”

Why this works

This signals:

You understand platform thinking (not feature thinking)
You balance customer + ecosystem + risk
You think in measurable adoption loops
You understand API businesses = developer experience businesses
